<HL>
   Who's News:
   Carnegie Mellon Chooses
   Mehrabian to Be President
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B12
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   PITTSBURGH -- Carnegie Mellon University named as its new
president Robert Mehrabian, dean of the College of
Engineering at the University of California at Santa Barbara.
   The 49-year-old Mr. Mehrabian will succeed Richard M.
Cyert, who is retiring June 30 after heading the university
for 18 years. Mr. Cyert is 68 years old.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Mehrabian, born in Tehran, Iran, is credited with
bringing UCSB's engineering college to national prominence,
Carnegie Mellon said. A metallurgist and mechanical engineer,
Mr. Mehrabian previously served as director of the Center for
Materials Science at the National Bureau of Standards.
   He earned his bachelor of science and doctor of science
degrees from Massachusetts Institute of Technology, where he
then became a professor.
</TEXT>
