<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Unjustified Implication
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<LP>
   Your March 7 Law-column item seems to imply that the State
Bar of Michigan had somehow sought to influence the
disposition of a now-dismissed complaint against its
president-elect. Complaints against lawyers in Michigan are
handled by an agency appointed for that purpose by the
Michigan Supreme Court, which is funded from state-bar dues.
No one outside the discipline agency even knew of the
existence of the complaint file. Even our president-elect,
who was the target, did not learn of its existence until the
incident was disclosed in a newspaper article long after the
file had been closed. Consequently, it was not possible for
the State Bar of Michigan to seek to influence the
disposition of the complaint, the existence of which was not
known. Further, the state bar has no control over the
operations of the Attorney Grievance Commission.
   Robert B. Webster
</LP>
<TEXT>
   President
   State Bar of Michigan
   Lansing, Mich.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900406-0138
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900406-0138.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Cabot Alters Plans,
   Will Buy Some Assets
   Of American Optical
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9A
</SO>
<CO>
   CBT MHC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WALTHAM, Mass. -- Cabot Corp. said it will buy all the
assets of American Optical Corp.'s AO Safety division in an
outright purchase by Cabot, instead of its previous plan to
have partial ownership of AO Safety through a joint venture.
   Terms of the new transaction, which is expected to be
completed later this month, weren't disclosed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cabot said it will merge AO Safety with Cabot's E-A-R
noise control and hearing protection business into a wholly
owned subsidiary, which is expected to have combined annual
revenue of about $200 million. AO Safety makes safety
eyeware, respirators and other safety products.
   Previously, Cabot had said it would form a limited
partnership with a unit of Manufacturers Hanover Corp. that
was going to acquire AO Safety from American Optical. In
addition, Cabot was going to contribute its E-A-R business to
the partnership. From that transaction, Cabot would have
received $100 million in cash and $30 million in securities,
plus a "significant" minority interest in the partnership.
   Cabot Chairman Samuel Bodman said, "As a result of certain
strategic and financial developments, we decided it was in
the best interest of Cabot to structure the transaction as an
outright purchase. This will have a positive impact on
earnings and provide more flexibility for financing in the
future."
   American Optical is based in Southbridge, Mass.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900406-0137
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900406-0137.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   47th Street's Orbach to Exit
   For a Software Start-Up
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9C
</SO>
<CO>
   WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Bobby Orbach, who turned discounter 47th
Street Photo into one of the nation's biggest independent
computer retailers, said he is leaving to start a new
software-related business.
   Mr. Orbach, 37 years old, who joined closely held 47th
Street in 1981 as a calculator salesman, spearheaded the
discounter's move into computers. Retail industry sources
estimate that last year 47th Street sold about $130 million
of computers and had total revenue of over $300 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Orbach managed the unlikely feat of making 47th Street
a major supplier of computers and software to big corporate
and government offices in the New York area. Although
computer and software companies once shunned 47th Street as
an unauthorized, gray-market discounter, many began to deal
with the retailer when it became a major outlet.
   Before getting into computers, 47th Street was primarily a
camera retailer, famous for low prices, high decibel
order-takers and Saturday closings (in keeping with the
Orthodox Jewish traditions of its owner and employees).
Irving Goldstein, owner of 47th Street, said the company
"regretfully accepted the resignation." Mr. Orbach said he
expects to announce his new venture by the end of May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
