<HL>
   Newsprint Production
   In Canada Fell 2.9%
   In February From '89
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C15
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<IN>
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- Canadian production of newsprint dropped 2.9%
in February from a year earlier, with the industry operating
at 94% of capacity.
   The Canadian Pulp and Paper Association, an industry
group, said Canadian mills produced 747,000 metric tons of
newsprint in February, down from 769,000 metric tons a year
earlier. The February 94% operating rate was unchanged from a
revised 94% in January but down from 100% a year earlier.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the first two months of the year, production fell 3.9%
to 1,544,000 metric tons from 1,607,000 metric tons a year
earlier. A metric ton equals 2,204.62 pounds.
   February shipments dropped 0.4% to 718,000 metric tons
from 721,000 metric tons a year earlier. Shipments within
Canada rose while shipments to the U.S. and other markets
fell. Shipments dropped 2.8% in the first two months to
1,434,000 metric tons from 1,475 metric tons in January and
February of 1989.
   The association said U.S. consumer stocks at the end of
February were 1,297,000 metric tons, a 38-day supply,
virtually unchanged from the end of January but down from a
42-day supply of 1,448,000 metric tons at the end of February
1989. Canadian mills' stocks at the end of February rose to
432,000 metric tons from 403,000 metric tons at the end of
January and 420,000 metric tons at the end of February 1989.
   Total U.S. consumption of newsprint fell 0.9% in February
to 920,000 metric tons from 929,000 metric tons a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
