<HL>
   Insurance Offered
   By London Firm
   In Takeover Fights
   ----
   By Tim Carrington
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14A
</SO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- For corporations, being the object of a takeover
war is economically similar to being hit by a hurricane or a
flood. So it isn't surprising that the insurance industry has
hatched a new policy that companies can buy for protection
against this modern catastrophe.
   TOI Corporate Services, a newly formed firm, is pushing
the new takeover insurance in collaboration with Robert
Fraser Group, a brokerage concern here. According to Sandra
Ringsell, one of TOI's founders, "we're the first to market"
takeover insurance, though others have sold it here and there
on a makeshift basis.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A sales brochure TOI is circulating highlights the
dizzying costs of being raided: for a company valued at more
than #30 million ($49.2 million), it can cost about #500,000
to fend off an unwanted suitor, according to TOI.
   Merchant bankers lay claim on the biggest chunk of these
costs, with about #320,000. Lawyers and stockbrokers grab
another #110,000. Public-relations people speak for another
#5,000, while accountants claim #35,000.
   Then there's all the extra time that executives at raided
companies have to put in. That can be insured too. For
coverage of #500,000 of takeover expenses, an insurance
policy costs as much as #25,000 a year. The premium doesn't
count as a takeover expense, however.
   Ms. Ringsell says she has pieced together
takeover-insurance policies through various underwriters for
about 35 companies. Now that TOI has been formed to
specialize in raider policies, she figures she will bring in
about 400 more.
   Although takeovers have slowed in the U.S. with the
collapse of the junk-bond market, TOI warns companies in
Europe that they aren't out of the woods yet. "Takeovers are
likely to increase," the company said in sales literature,
partly because "companies will be seeking to be better
positioned in their respective markets ahead of 1992."
   So far, Ms. Ringsell said, only one policyholder has filed
a claim. Everything went smoothly: The company got reimbursed
for the costs of repulsing the raider, and it came back to
renew its policy for another year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900406-0107
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900406-0107.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   BankWorcester Corp.
   To Add $11.9 Million
   To Loan-Loss Reserve
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   BNKW RBS+
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   WORCESTER, Mass. -- BankWorcester Corp., citing a
"dramatically weakened" real-estate market, said it will add
$11.9 million to its allowance for possible loan losses,
resulting in a loss for the first quarter -- and possibly
jeopardizing its agreement to be acquired by a Rhode
Island-based subsidiary of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC.
   In the year-earlier first quarter, BankWorcester had net
income of $2.8 million, or 38 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company said it has charged off about $9.1 million of
loans, and said that after the provisions and charge-offs,
the loan-loss allowance will be about $14.4 million, or 1.5%
of loans outstanding. It said nonperforming assets total
about $44.5 million.
   As reported, BankWorcester has agreed to be acquired by
Royal Bank's Citizens Financial Group Inc. unit for $22.50 a
share, or about $149 million.
   One condition of the acquisition agreement, however,
provides that Citizens can terminate the agreement if
nonperforming assets and other items exceed $50 million after
all regulatory approvals for the acquisition have been
received. As of March 31, BankWorcester said, the level of
nonperforming assets and other items covered by the condition
totaled $58.6 million.
   BankWorcester said that the total is expected to fluctuate
over time and noted that the $50 million benchmark comes into
effect after receipt of all regulatory approvals.
   The company said, "The management of BankWorcester
believes that it will be able to meet this condition at that
point in time; however, there can be no assurance that this
condition will in fact be satisfied at that future time."
</TEXT>
