<HL>
   Thursday's Markets:
   Wary Mood
   Dampens
   U.S. Trading
   ---
   Fears About Tokyo,
   U.S. Economy Keep
   Stocks, Bonds Flat
   ----
   By Douglas R. Sease
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   Wariness about the Tokyo stock market, the U.S. economy
and the fate of the dollar kept a tight lid on financial
markets.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average eked out a gain of 1.80
points to 2721.17 in light trading. But the advance was
concentrated in blue-chip issues. Broader market averages
were off slightly. Long-term bond prices eased, and the
dollar was mixed.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said worries about Japanese stocks restrained
U.S. stock prices. The Dow industrials lost more than 17
points Wednesday after rumors spread that a big player in the
Japanese stock market was in financial trouble. The Nikkei
index of 225 stocks lost about 1,200 points in early trading
Thursday, but recouped most of that by the end of trading.
   Treasury bonds, which benefited Wednesday from a flight to
safety on the unconfirmed Tokyo rumors, were nearly moribund
yesterday as investors awaited this morning's March
employment report. Economists expect the report to show the
economy generated about 178,000 non-farm jobs last month,
substantially below the growth rate in January and February.
   Currency traders, meantime, awaited the results this
weekend of the Group of Seven major industrialized nations
meeting in Paris, where officials will discuss steps to rein
in the dollar's surge against the Japanese yen. Although
traders don't expect any such efforts to be successful in the
long run, they nevertheless bid the dollar lower against the
yen yesterday.
   Charles Clough, chief portfolio strategist at Merrill
Lynch, said investors are correct to be concerned about the
Tokyo stock market. If nothing else, the disruptions there
could undermine investor confidence in the U.S. market. But
he added that even if Tokyo's troubles spread to the U.S.,
any turmoil is likely to be short-lived. He said U.S.
interest rates are among the lowest in the world, the dollar
is strong and Americans are saving an ever-growing portion of
their incomes -- all signs of fundamental economic strength.
   "Right now, Japan is a loose cannon," he said. "But I
think that if we did see the U.S. markets destabilized, it
wouldn't last long."
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices crept higher in light trading. Volume on the
New York Stock Exchange totaled 144.2 million shares. But
declining issues on the Big Board were ahead of gainers 744
to 703.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices eased. The benchmark 30-year Treasury bond
lost an eighth of a point, or $1.25 for each $1,000 face
amount. The yield on the issue rose to 8.51%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar was mixed. In late New York trading, the
currency was quoted at 1.6995 marks, unchanged from
Wednesday, and at 157.4 yen, down from 158.95.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900406-0070
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900406-0070.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   Mitterrand's East Bank
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP FREST
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   The politics of Eastern Europe have held the world's
attention. But if these brave people are to succeed, the
world had better keep paying attention when the talk turns to
the harder subject of money. This weekend at the G-7 meeting
in Paris, finance ministers will hear that a $12 billion
development bank will do wonders for Eastern Europe. In fact,
history suggests that it will prolong the shift from
socialism to capitalism.
   The Eastern European Development Bank (EEDB), with 27
Western and seven East European member nations, was largely
the brainchild of French President Francois Mitterrand. He
insisted that the European Community provide most of the
capital and make most of the decisions. The U.S., Japan and
the Soviet Union each are invited to chip in 8.5% to 10% of
the capital.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. was leery of French insistence that 40% of the
lending in Eastern Europe go to governments rather than
private firms, but it went along. It is drawing a line,
however, on loans to the Soviet Union. Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady told Congress that the U.S. won't join if the
Soviets are allowed to borrow more than their share of the
capital. He noted that the Soviet Union is clearly not yet an
emerging democracy. Since it still spends 15% to 20% of its
GNP on defense it has ample resources to finance perestroika.
   But U.S. concerns go deeper. If the record of the World
Bank and its offshoots is any guide, an EEDB would help
preserve statism. The French insist that the EEDB will be
different, with 60% of its loans going to the private sector.
But this is a distinction without a difference.
   Such bodies fund private-sector borrowers by giving the
money to state-run development banks whose bureaucrats then
"on-loan" to private borrowers of their choosing. Last year a
World Bank internal report noted that in a sample of 18 of
these "directed credit" programs, an average of nearly 50% of
loans were in arrears. Yet, the first World Bank loan to
post-communist Poland this February was $265 million to the
National Bank for "directed credit" to export industries. Is
it likely that the EEDB's private-sector lending will be more
rational?
   Such infusions often act as a narcotic, delaying needed
economic reforms and thus making matters worse. Politicians
can't help but look at aid as a way to delay privatizations
and painful price reforms. The Czechs seem to agree.
President Vaclav Havel told Margaret Thatcher during his
British visit that "we value your advice and moral support
far more than your money."
   U.S. policymakers are going along with the EEDB partly out
of concern that the U.S. will be ridiculed if it doesn't. But
rather than fret about its image, the U.S. should stand up
for the incentive-based policies that the rest of the world
is now emulating.
   Any money the U.S. does send to Eastern Europe would be
better spent in the forms recommended by the commission on
Hungary, whose conclusions are summarized in an article
nearby (See: "A Recipe for a Free-Market Hungary" -- WSJ
April 6, 1990). Additionally, Eastern Europeans could be
brought to the U.S. to work as trainees and interns, much the
way American corporations routinely bring foreign nationals
to the U.S. for intensive training.
   The West should be helping Eastern Europe. But the
proposed EEDB looks no better than the other development
banks. If they are so good, how come so many of their Third
World clients are still doing so badly?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900406-0069
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900406-0069.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Talks on International
   Telecharge Sale End;
   Two Top Posts Filled
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   ITI WNEWS MCIC
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- International Telecharge Inc. said that talks
about a possible sale of the company have ended and that
Allan L. Rayfield, a former telecommunications executive, was
named chairman and chief executive officer.
   The company, which provides operator-assisted
long-distance service to hotels, hospitals and pay phones,
said that discussions to sell the company to a suitor ended
before a formal offer was made. The potential acquirer wasn't
disclosed. International Telecharge said last month that it
had received an inquiry about a possible acquisition.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company also said that it named Mr. Rayfield, a
company director, to the two top posts, succeeding Edmund F.
Tagg, who was chairman, chief executive officer and
president. Mr. Tagg, who remains a director, now will serve
as president and chief operating officer, succeeding Dennis
Geraghty, formerly chief operating officer, who resigned, the
company said.
   Mr. Rayfield was a senior vice president and director of
GTE Corp. until a year ago. Since then, he has been a
consultant.
   International Telecharge also said that it has agreed to
provide operator services to hotel and hospital customers of
MCI Communications Corp. as part of an agreement calling for
International Telecharge to become a large customer of MCI's
long-distance network. International Telecharge said the pact
reduces its long-distance line costs, and that it calls for
MCI to market its operator, billing and collection services
for hotels under the MCI name.
   As part of the agreement, MCI returned warrants to
purchase 2,986,895 International Telecharge shares to
International Telecharge and agreed to provide a
working-capital loan of undisclosed size to defray
development costs for the hospitality services.
   In American Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
International Telecharge rose 12.5 cents to close at $3.125 a
share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
