<HL>
   Business Brief -- Oracle Systems Corp.:
   Shareholders File Lawsuits
   Over Decline in Stock Price
</HL>
<DATE>
04/06/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4B
</SO>
<CO>
   ORCL
</CO>
<LP>
   A dozen shareholder lawsuits have been filed against
Belmont, Calif.-based software maker Oracle Systems Corp.
after last week's 31% plunge in the company's stock price.
   The lead suit by stockholder John Coleman alleges that
Oracle made false and misleading forecasts of its
third-quarter earnings and that the company failed to
disclose that two large contracts wouldn't be completed.
Oracle called the suit "meritless."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In record one-day volume for an over-the-counter issue,
Oracle stock tumbled March 28, the day after the company
reported flat third-quarter earnings of 18 cents a share.
Analysts had expected earnings would be between 25 cents and
29 cents a share.
   The stock dropped $7.825 to close at $17.50 with nearly 21
million of the company's 129 million shares changing hands.
The stock price peaked March 19, at $28.125.
</TEXT>
